<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1802,2045]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1802,1828]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[274,565,1802,1828]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[274,565,1802,1828]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Macrogomphus phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described, in detail, on the basis of two males and a female from W. Borneo, Singkawang, swamped forest near “Bakoean” (Bakuan, 
<collectingRegion box="[838,1144,1838,1865]" country="Indonesia" name="Kalimantan Barat" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Kalimantan Barat Province</collectingRegion>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[1181,1294,1838,1865]" name="Indonesia" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
), as “closely resembling 
<taxonomicName authority="Selys" authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1878" box="[285,701,1874,1900]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="parallelogramma" subSpecies="albardae">
<emphasis box="[285,630,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="78">M. parallelogramma albardae</emphasis>
Selys
</taxonomicName>
but much smaller and with differently shaped anal appendages’ (
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[158,386,1909,1936]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 201</bibRefCitation>
). In the diagnosis, such details as “shorter discoidal triangle of the front wing, ... narrower and almost parallel-sided yellow bands on each side of the thorax, and ... more widely separated and more obliquely placed antehumeral thoracic stripes” were mentioned (
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[768,999,1981,2008]" pageId="21" pageNumber="78" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 203</bibRefCitation>
). The female was stated to differ from other species by a bifid median prominence on the occipital plate (which was not figured).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
Lieftinck abstained from verbal description and comparison of the male anal appendages of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[1244,1392,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[1244,1392,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but made a confusing statement: “The shape of the inner branch of the sup. anal apps. of the male rather suggests 
<taxonomicName authority="Fraser" authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1933" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borikhanensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. borikhanensis</emphasis>
Fraser
</taxonomicName>
, from the 
<collectingCountry box="[498,552,225,251]" name="Laos" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Laos</collectingCountry>
country...” (
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[689,916,224,251]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935: 203</bibRefCitation>
). The (incorrect) drawing of the appendages of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fraser" authorityYear="1933" box="[151,346,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="borikhanensis">
<emphasis box="[151,346,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. borikhanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fraser, F. C." box="[388,534,261,287]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="109 - 141" refId="ref18133" refString="Fraser, F. C. (1933) Dragonflies of the Laos country. Journal of Siam Society, Natural History Supplement, 9, 109 - 141." type="journal article" year="1933">Fraser (1933</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 6a, c; see 
<figureCitation box="[700,780,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1818,1843]" captionTargetBox="[361,1227,186,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[350,1237,166,1806]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Anal appendages (a–h) and secondary genitalia (j–k) of Macrogomphus albardae as illustrated in literature: aafter Lieftinck (1935: fig. 9) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); b—after Orr (2005: p. 64) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); c—after Fraser (1933: fig. 8a, c) (as M. borikhanensis); d—after Asahina (1986: fig. 8–9) (as? M. phalantus): e, j—after Asahina (1986: fig. 4–6) (as M. borikhanensis); f, i—after Chao (1982: fig. 1, 3, 6) (as M. guilinensis); g—after Wilson (2005: fig. 17 d, e) (as M. guilinensis); h—after Karube (2014: fig. 13) (as M. guilinensis). Not to scale; j mirrored. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swelling of the cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995329/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 3c</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[792,820,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1914,1939]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 8. Holotype of Macrogomphus borikhanensis Fraser, 1933 and its labels (BMNH): a—dorsal view; b—lateral view. Not to scale. Courtesy of Benjamin Price." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995339/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">8d</figureCitation>
here) hardly resembles their structure in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[1281,1429,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[1281,1429,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In fact, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[240,389,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[240,389,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits an unique distinct diagnostic character: in dorsal view, the proximal inner swelling of the cercus is very sharp and prominent, and shifted distally off the cercus cleft into its two branches, as indicated with an asterisk in 
<figureCitation box="[366,459,368,395]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1898,1923]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,166,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[227,1361,166,1886]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 15. Details of male specimens of Macrogomphus phalantus: a–f—M. p. jayavarman subsp; nov., the holotype; gh—M. p. phalantus (After Lieftinck 1935: figs.11–12); a—head, frontal view; b–c,g—secondary genitalia, lateral view; d—anal appendages, dorsal view; e—ditto, lateral view; f—ditto, ventral view; h—dorsal and lateral view. Scale bar 1 mm. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swellings of the cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995353/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 15h</figureCitation>
(after 
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[536,706,368,395]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 12). As a consequence, two more distal swellings are ‘compressed’ to locate closely to each other (
<figureCitation box="[607,706,404,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1898,1923]" captionTargetBox="[227,1361,166,1861]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[227,1361,166,1886]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 15. Details of male specimens of Macrogomphus phalantus: a–f—M. p. jayavarman subsp; nov., the holotype; gh—M. p. phalantus (After Lieftinck 1935: figs.11–12); a—head, frontal view; b–c,g—secondary genitalia, lateral view; d—anal appendages, dorsal view; e—ditto, lateral view; f—ditto, ventral view; h—dorsal and lateral view. Scale bar 1 mm. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swellings of the cerci." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995353" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995353/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 15h</figureCitation>
). In all illustrations and specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[1141,1279,405,431]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albardae">
<emphasis box="[1141,1279,405,431]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. albardae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to the author (
<figureCitation box="[238,330,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1868,1893]" captionTargetBox="[187,1400,166,1856]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[187,1400,166,1856]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Details of some male specimens of Macrogomphus albardae kept in RMNH (courtesy of Jan van Tol): a–d—the male syntype (the labels ‘Holotype’ are misleading); e—“W. Borneo, 0 m. / Singkawang / Penanring / L. Coomans de Ruiter / 24. II. 1932”; f—“S. Sumatra / Terbanggi-Hilir / nr. Menggala / Lampang distr. / 18. VIII. 1936 / M. Bartels”; a—general habitus; b, e–f—S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view; c—head and thorax, dorsolateral view; d—labels of the male syntype. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995327/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Figs. 2b</figureCitation>
,e–f, 3a–h, 4c, 7a,c, 9a, 11), the proximal inner swelling (indicated by an asterisk in 
<figureCitation box="[1271,1344,441,467]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1815,1840]" captionTargetBox="[413,1211,196,1803]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[376,1211,174,1803]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Details of the specimens identified as Macrogomphus parallelogramma s. str.: the holotype female (a) and males (b–i), as illustrated by Hagen in Selys (1858: planche 5, fig. 5 and planche 20, fig. 4) (a–f); of a male specimen from “Java mer.” from RBINS collection (Courtesy of Jérôme Constant) (g–j): and of a male specimen from “W. Java. 100 m. /, Djaniga / Tjibarangbang / 30.IV.1939 / over stream p.m. / M.A. Lieftinck” and kept in RMNH (courtesy of Jan van Tol) (k,l); a—head, dorsal view; b,h—S8–10 (dorsal view); c,i—ditto (lateral view); d—S10 and appendages, lateral view; e—epiproct, ventral view; f–g,k—cerci, posteriodorsal view; j–k—labels.Asterisk marks the bulge of the inner cercus margin. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995325" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995325/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Fig. 1l</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[1399,1428,441,468]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1818,1843]" captionTargetBox="[361,1227,186,1806]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[350,1237,166,1806]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Anal appendages (a–h) and secondary genitalia (j–k) of Macrogomphus albardae as illustrated in literature: aafter Lieftinck (1935: fig. 9) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); b—after Orr (2005: p. 64) (as M. parallelogramma albardae); c—after Fraser (1933: fig. 8a, c) (as M. borikhanensis); d—after Asahina (1986: fig. 8–9) (as? M. phalantus): e, j—after Asahina (1986: fig. 4–6) (as M. borikhanensis); f, i—after Chao (1982: fig. 1, 3, 6) (as M. guilinensis); g—after Wilson (2005: fig. 17 d, e) (as M. guilinensis); h—after Karube (2014: fig. 13) (as M. guilinensis). Not to scale; j mirrored. Asterisk indicates the proximal inner swelling of the cercus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3995329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3995329/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">3b</figureCitation>
) is smoother and invariably located at the level of the cleft, more proximal swellings also being smoother. The importance of this character could be disputable if I had not collect a series of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[1003,1178,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1178,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males with exactly the same cerci as far from the presumed range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[663,811,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[663,811,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as in 
<collectingCountry box="[877,995,549,575]" name="Cambodia" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
, but in a similar habitat (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
Later the species was reported for Palembang in eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[857,950,585,611]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[968,1143,584,611]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="1 - 202" refId="ref18965" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1954) Handlist of Malaysian Odonata. A catalogue of the dragonflies of the Malay Peninsula, Sumatra, Java and Borneo, including the adjacent small islands. Treubia, 22 (Supplement), 1 - 202." type="journal article" year="1954">Lieftinck 1954</bibRefCitation>
). All so scanty reports of this species refer to a habitat unusual for gomphids: swamped forest in low country (
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[1101,1272,620,647]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck 1935</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[1284,1343,620,647]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="67 - 87" refId="ref19012" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1955) Synopsis of the dragonflies (Odonata) of Ceylon. Zoologische Mededelingen, 34 (5), 67 - 87." type="journal article" year="1955">1955</bibRefCitation>
), a river upstream the 
<taxonomicName box="[302,361,658,683]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Nypa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[302,361,658,683]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Nypa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
stand and mangroves in lowland rainforest (Dow 2016). The ‘snorkel’ of the elongated terminal abdominal segments of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[465,640,693,719]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[465,640,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae suggest ability to live in silt low of oxygen, nevertheless other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" box="[151,326,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,326,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are usually found near running water at foothills and mountains.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,153,971]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">
While studying 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[380,475,765,791]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Odonata</taxonomicName>
of the great Lake Tonlé Sap in 
<collectingCountry box="[835,950,765,791]" name="Cambodia" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
I was struck to find numerous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1858" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">Macrogomphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. at a temporarily inundated forest margin on its northern bank (at the low water season). The male anal appendages appeared to correspond to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1935" box="[588,735,837,863]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantus">
<emphasis box="[588,735,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the unusual habitat was exactly as in that species. Certain differences of the collected specimens from the original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lieftinck, M. A." box="[936,1121,872,899]" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" pagination="175 - 207" refId="ref18933" refString="Lieftinck, M. A. (1935) New and little known Odonata of the Oriental and Australian Regions. Treubia, 15 (2), 175 - 207." type="journal article" year="1935">Lieftinck (1935)</bibRefCitation>
, as well as the huge distance of the newly found population from the presumed range of 
<taxonomicName box="[821,959,909,935]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Macrogomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="22" pageNumber="79" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phalantu">
<emphasis box="[821,959,909,935]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="79">M. phalantu</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s in Borneo and Sumatra, suggested a new subspecies which is described below.
</paragraph>
